The paper focuses on unsupervised learning and designing structural priors to learn meaningful features while minimizing the description length of the representations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses convolutional neural networks and activation functions, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) research. The paper also discusses the interpretability of the learned kernels, which is a topic of interest in the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a new method for decomposing and compressing data, which could fall under the signal processing (cs.SI) sub-category.
